 `randn`/`randexp`","user":{"login":"mikmoore","id":95002244,"node_id":"U_kgDOBamehA","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/95002244?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore","html_url":"https://github.com/mikmoore","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mikmoore/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"body":"The pattern `log(rand(rng))` has the consequence of permitting `log(0.0) == -Inf` to be computed, since the domain of `rand` is $[0,1)$. It looks like this mishap wouldn't actually escape `randn` (due to exit conditionals), but it appears that it can escape `randexp`, resulting in a return value of `+Inf`. While this is a literally admissible return value, it is grossly over-represented. On the current version, it occurs with probability roughly $10^{-18}$. For reference, values $>41$ should occur about that often. The correct return frequency for values that exceed `floatmax(Float64)` (i.e., `+Inf`) should be roughly $10^{-10^{308}}$.

Replacing `log(rand(rng))` with `log1p(-rand(rng))` is "statistically identical" (modulo the effects of finite representations) except that it equivalently shifts the support of inputs to `log` from $[0,1)$ to the better-behaved $(0,1]$.

